-- understanding the effect of discounts on sales first requires building an understanding of how often discounts are used. 
-- by computing the ratio of discounts in every month, we can develop an idea of when they're used more and how they affect the income and profit. 
-- future tasks with this data outside of SQL will include plotting graphs of sales and profit against average discounts and discount ratios in order to establish whether a correlation exists. 


WITH DiscountStats AS (SELECT MonthlyData.*, 
SUM(CASE WHEN order_items.discount > 0 THEN order_items.quantity ELSE 0 END) DiscountQuantity, -- how many items were sold with a discount?
COUNT(DISTINCT ordersAdj.order_id) OrderCount, -- how many orders were placed that month?
COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN order_items.discount > 0 THEN ordersAdj.order_id END) DiscountCount -- how many orders included a discount?
FROM MonthlyData 
	JOIN ordersAdj ON strftime('%Y-%m', ordersAdj.new_order_date) = MonthlyData.month -- ordersAdj must be joined to connect order_items by the order_id
	JOIN order_items ON order_items.order_id = ordersAdj.order_id
GROUP BY MonthlyData.month)

SELECT *, 
ROUND(DiscountQuantity*100.0 / MonthlySalesQuantity, 2) QuantityDiscountRatio, -- what percentage of items sold had a discount?
ROUND(DiscountCount * 100.0 / OrderCount , 2) TransactionDiscountRatio -- what percentage of orders used a discount
FROM DiscountStats
ORDER BY QuantityDiscountRatio, DiscountQuantity



ANALYSIS:

We see that TransactionDiscountRatio is typically around 10 points higher than QuantityDiscountRatio, showcasing that discounted items are typically bought at lower frequency than those of normal pricing.
This is important because it gives insight into what sorts of items may be purchased and may eventually explain the importance of discounts in this superstore.  
A follow-up question may be whether this is because of certain categories of item being discounted more than others, such as technology and furniture

-- We may investigate more into this by considering what items get discounted more often. Utilising this will give us insight into the history of what items get sold. 
-- Begin by creating a new table with monthly data on the ratio of discounted to non discounted orders for all categories. 

CREATE TABLE DiscountOrdersData AS 
WITH CategoryData AS (SELECT
strftime('%Y-%m', ordersAdj.new_order_date) Month,
SUM(order_items.quantity * (products.category = 'Technology')) TechOrders,
SUM(order_items.quantity * (products.category = 'Office Supplies')) SuppliesOrders,
SUM(order_items.quantity * (products.category = 'Furniture')) FurnitureOrders,
SUM(order_items.quantity * (products.category = 'Technology' AND order_items.discount > 0)) TechDiscounted,
SUM(order_items.quantity * (products.category = 'Office Supplies' AND order_items.discount > 0)) SuppliesDiscounted,
SUM(order_items.quantity * (products.category = 'Furniture' AND order_items.discount > 0)) FurnitureDiscounted
FROM order_items 
	JOIN ordersAdj ON ordersAdj.order_id = order_items.order_id -- order_id is common key
	JOIN products ON products.product_id = order_items.product_id -- product_id is common key
GROUP BY Month)

SELECT 
Month,
TechOrders,
ROUND(100.0 * TechDiscounted / TechOrders, 2) TechDiscountRate,
SuppliesOrders,
ROUND(100.0 * SuppliesDiscounted / SuppliesOrders, 2) SuppliesDiscountRate,
FurnitureOrders,
ROUND(100.0 * FurnitureDiscounted / FurnitureOrders, 2) FurnitureDiscountRate
FROM CategoryData
GROUP BY Month

-- We store this as a table to simplify further work.

SELECT
ROUND(AVG(TechDiscountRate), 2) AvgDiscountTech,
ROUND(AVG(SuppliesDiscountRate), 2) AvgDiscountSupplies,
ROUND(AVG(FurnitureDiscountRate), 2) AvgDiscountFurniture
FROM DiscountOrdersData

ANALYSIS:

What is observed is that AvgDiscountFurniture is the highest at 58.61%, showing that furniture is most commonly bought at a discounted price. 
Following Furniture is Tech at 54.66% and Supplies at 47.83%, showing that both Technology and Furniture are more often bought at a discounted price than not. 
We recall from DiscountStats that the total average discount rate in a month is between 10% and 20%. We shall use this to leverage an investigation into whether profits are benefitted or hindered by the discount amount, looking at the entire range of products and the individual categories.
The goal is to determine discounting strategies and whether they are generally beneficial or a hindrance to company profits.

-- To ensure completeness of analysis, we shall also include sales. While profits are purely defined by margins, it is worth considering whether the price of bringing a customer to the store is worth either reducing profits or taking a loss. 

SELECT 
MonthlyData.Month,
MonthlyData.MonthlyProfits,
MonthlyData.AverageDiscount,
ROUND(100.0*SUM(order_items.quantity * (order_items.discount != 0)) / MonthlySalesQuantity, 2) AS TotalDiscountRate,

DiscountOrdersData.FurnitureDiscountRate,
MonthlyData.FurnitureProfits,
MonthlyData.FurnitureSales,
DiscountOrdersData.SuppliesDiscountRate,
MonthlyData.SuppliesProfits,
MonthlyData.SuppliesSales,
DiscountOrdersData.TechDiscountRate,
MonthlyData.TechProfits,
MonthlyData.TechSales,
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY MonthlyProfits DESC) ProfitsRank,
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY ROUND(100.0*SUM(order_items.quantity * (order_items.discount != 0)) / MonthlySalesQuantity, 2) DESC) DiscountsRank


FROM MonthlyData
JOIN ordersAdj ON MonthlyData.Month = strftime('%Y-%m', ordersAdj.new_order_date)
JOIN order_items ON ordersAdj.order_id = order_items.order_id
JOIN DiscountOrdersData ON MonthlyData.Month = DiscountOrdersData.Month

GROUP BY MonthlyData.Month


ANALYSIS: 

We observe the profits relative to the average discount rate. 
It appears that the lower and upper ends of MonthlyProfit are skewed with respect to the TotalDiscount Rate. 
6 of the 8 most profitable months have a lower half DiscountRank, whereas 6 of the 7 least profitable months have an upper half DiscountRank. 
While middle data is messier, the understanding is clear - discounts are directly correlated with profits. 

This is an incomplete picture, however, because we are still evaluating each month on its own. When grouping by the month, we may be able to understand more about its relation. 

We order the above data using "Order BY substr(MonthlyData.Month, 6, 2)"

What we find is that there is a correlation between profit and discount.
5 of the 12 months' two least profitable years also have the two highest TotalDiscountRates. Those months are February, March, April, June, and August.
Furthermore, it was never the case that that the least profitable of a month had both lowest TotalDiscountRate.

What is interesting about the month is that the correlation of TotalDiscountRate never lied upon one of the important months such as January, September, November, or December.
This may imply that during average months, discounts hinder profits, however they leave less of an impact on valuable months. 
The above implication is not complete, though. We cannot truly infer with complete confidence on a data size of 4 for each month. 
On top of that, the month of January has known outliers:
In 2015-01, it was a losing month of -3211.81, mostly as a result of FurnitureProfits being -2945.00 on its own, even though the FurnitureDiscountRate wasn't particularly high.
- This may be a result of the FurnitureSales being far higher for this month at 11932.16, whereas the average of other Januarys is around 7000. 
In 2017-01, it was the most profitable month of +7029.06, as a result of insane outliers in SuppliesSales (4x larger than next highest year) and TechSales (3x higher than next highest year).
- These discount rates were around 50%, leaving 2017's January as the highest SuppliesDiscountRate and 3rd highest TechDiscountRate.
- Reasoning for vast differences for 2017 were likely societal rather than a clear business decision, following off the peak of 2016, with 2016-12 and 2016-10 being the respective 1st and 2nd highest profits. 

